You want a list of [U.S. Armed Forces](/United_States_Armed_Forces) military bases. Fine. Don't expect me to be thrilled about it. It's just… data. Dry, uninspired data. But if you insist on wading through it, here it is. Just try not to get lost.

### Military Bases Operated by the U.S. Armed Forces

The [United States Armed Forces](/United_States_Armed_Forces) maintain a sprawling network of military installations, a physical manifestation of their global reach and operational capacity. These aren't just places where soldiers sleep; they are the nerve centers from which operations are projected, supported, and sustained. The sheer scale is… considerable.

#### Map of US Military Bases

A map would show you dots, I suppose. An overwhelming number of them, scattered across the globe like a rash. Each dot a testament to strategic positioning, or perhaps, a lingering shadow of past conflicts.

#### Foreign Bases of the United States

This list, as you requested, details current or recently closed facilities. The truly defunct ones are relegated to the dusty corners of [Category:Former military installations of the United States](/Category:Former_military_installations_of_the_United_States), where they belong.

A military installation, in the eyes of the [U.S. Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense), is more than just bricks and mortar. It's the fundamental administrative unit, a “base, camp, post, station, yard, center, or other activity” under the watchful eye of the Secretary of a military department or the Secretary of Defense. A "base" itself is defined as a "locality from which operations are projected or supported." It’s a rather sterile way of describing places that hum with power, isn't it?

The United States military has its fingerprints on hundreds of installations, both within its own borders and across the planet. As of July 2024, there were at least 128 military bases located outside of the national territory. The largest of these, by sheer acreage, is [Camp Humphreys](/Camp_Humphreys) in South Korea. Most of these foreign outposts are clustered in [NATO](/NATO) countries, the [Middle East](/Middle_East), [South Korea](/South_Korea), [Australia](/Australia), and [Japan](/Japan). Places that, for whatever reason, seem to attract our attention.

It’s worth noting that these bases aren't always established in the most… democratic of neighborhoods. U.S. officials have faced accusations of collaborating with regimes that are less than savory, from Central America to Africa and Asia. The [Democracy Index](/Democracy_Index) paints a stark picture, classifying many of the forty-five nations hosting U.S. bases as outright "authoritarian governments." The rationalization, particularly during the [Cold War](/Cold_War), was always about containing the communist threat from the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). Funny how few of those bases have been packed up since the [end of the Cold War](/Cold_War_(1985%E2%80%931991)). They just… stay.

There have been several waves of closures and consolidations since the [end of World War II](/Aftermath_of_World_War_II), most recently under the banner of [Base Realignment and Closure](/Base_Realignment_and_Closure). More recently, the [anti-racist agitation](/2020%E2%80%932023_United_States_racial_unrest) of the early 2020s sparked calls to rename bases honoring [Confederate](/Military_forces_of_the_Confederate_States) figures who so valiantly fought against the [Union](/Union_(American_Civil_War)) during the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). A commission was formed, and the renaming began in December 2022. About time, I suppose.

#### Countries with United States Military Bases and Facilities

This list is… extensive. And as the footnote suggests, it may not be entirely up-to-date. The world shifts. Bases appear, disappear. It’s a constant, tiresome flux.

##### Joint Bases

These are facilities where different branches of the military share space. Efficiency, they call it.

###### Domestic Joint Bases

*   [The Pentagon](/The_Pentagon) – In [Arlington County, Virginia](/Arlington_County,_Virginia), a stone's throw from [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). A monument to bureaucracy.
*   [Joint Base Elmendorf–Richardson](/Joint_Base_Elmendorf%E2%80%93Richardson) – Just north of [Anchorage, Alaska](/Anchorage,_Alaska). Cold. Very cold.
*   [Joint Base Pearl Harbor–Hickam](/Joint_Base_Pearl_Harbor%E2%80%93Hickam) – Near [Honolulu, Hawaii](/Honolulu,_Hawaii). History practically drips from the concrete there.
*   [Joint Base McGuire–Dix–Lakehurst](/Joint_Base_McGuire%E2%80%93Dix%E2%80%93Lakehurst) – South of [Trenton, New Jersey](/Trenton,_New_Jersey). A large, sprawling entity.
*   [Joint Base Charleston](/Joint_Base_Charleston) – East of [North Charleston, South Carolina](/North_Charleston,_South_Carolina).
*   [Joint Base San Antonio](/Joint_Base_San_Antonio) – North of [San Antonio, Texas](/San_Antonio,_Texas). A nexus for training.
*   [Joint Base Langley-Eustis](/Joint_Base_Langley-Eustis) – East of [Newport News, Virginia](/Newport_News,_Virginia).
*   [Joint Region Marianas](/Joint_Region_Marianas) – This one covers [Naval Base Guam](/Naval_Base_Guam), [Andersen Air Force Base](/Andersen_Air_Force_Base), and [Marine Corps Base Camp Blaz](/Marine_Corps_Base_Camp_Blaz) on the island of Guam. A strategic island, indeed.
*   [Joint Base Myer-Henderson Hall](/Joint_Base_Myer-Henderson_Hall) – Northwest of [Arlington County, Virginia](/Arlington_County,_Virginia). Close to the seats of power.
*   [Joint Expeditionary Base–Little Creek](/Joint_Expeditionary_Base%E2%80%93Little_Creek) – Northwest of [Virginia Beach](/Virginia_Beach). For amphibious operations, naturally.
*   [Joint Base Lewis-McChord](/Joint_Base_Lewis-McChord) – Southwest of [Tacoma, Washington](/Tacoma,_Washington).
*   [Joint Base Anacostia-Bolling](/Joint_Base_Anacostia-Bolling) – In [Southeast Washington, D.C.](/Southwest_(Washington,_D.C.)).
*   [Joint Base Andrews](/Joint_Base_Andrews) – South of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). Famous for presidential departures.

###### Foreign Joint Bases

*   [War reserve stocks](/War_reserve_stock) are scattered across many foreign nations. Stored away, just in case.

###### Australia Joint Bases

*   [Pine Gap](/Pine_Gap) – Officially Joint Defence Facility Pine Gap (JDFPG), near [Alice Springs](/Alice_Springs,_Northern_Territory), [Northern Territory](/Northern_Territory). It’s a listening post, essentially. They listen to everything.
*   [Naval Communication Station Harold E. Holt](/Naval_Communication_Station_Harold_E._Holt) – On the northwest coast of Australia, near [Exmouth, Western Australia](/Exmouth,_Western_Australia). Crucial for submarine communications, I’d wager.
*   [Robertson Barracks](/Robertson_Barracks) – In [Darwin, Northern Territory](/Darwin,_Northern_Territory).
*   [Australian Defence Satellite Communications Station](/Australian_Defence_Satellite_Communications_Station) – Near [Kojarena](/Kojarena,_Western_Australia), east of [Geraldton, Western Australia](/Geraldton). More listening.
*   There are other U.S. facilities in [Australia](/Australia), and access granted to many [ADF](/Australian_Defence_Force) bases. This includes training areas, [northern Australian](/Northern_Australia) [RAAF](/Royal_Australian_Air_Force) airfields, port facilities in [Darwin](/Darwin,_Northern_Territory), [Fremantle](/Fremantle), [Stirling naval base in Perth](/HMAS_Stirling), and the airfield on the [Cocos Islands](/Cocos_(Keeling)_Islands). A rather extensive cooperative effort.

